<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08172b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08172b">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08172b"> 172(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Dermot Mac Murrogh of / Leinster wrongs / O&apos;Rorke, Breffni / banished by O&apos;Connor / goes to Aquitaine to H. II / enrols Robert de Clair / Pembroke / promises Eva &amp; crown</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The story of Dermot McMurrough, king of Leinster, and his part in the invasion, has often been told &hellip; How he foully wronged the honour of O&apos;Rorke, a chieftain of Connaught; how &hellip; he was upon the accession of Roderick O&apos;Connor driven away from Ireland; how he fled to England to do homage to Henry, and seek his protection; how, finding him gone to Aquitaine, he followed him there, and in return for his vows of allegiance received letters authorizing the king&apos;s subjects to enlist if they choose for the Irish service; how armed with these he went to Wales, and there succeeded in recruiting a band of mixed Norman and Norman-Welsh adventurers &hellip; Of the recruits thus enlisted the most important was Robert de Clair, Earl of Pembroke and Chepstow, nicknamed by his contemporaries, Strongbow, whom Dermot met at Bristol, and won over by a double bribe&mdash;the hand, namely of his daughter Eva, and the succession to the sovereignty of Leinster&mdash;a succession which, upon the Irish mode of election, he had, it may be observed, no shadow of right to dispose of. <small> Emily Lawless, <a name="ELIS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ELIS"><cite title="source">Ireland (Story of Nations series</cite></a> (192?) 81</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
